# 📡 Section 03 — Objectives

> **Learning Objective:** After reading this section, you will know exactly which objective to choose for your print job, how to install it safely, and why your choice affects everything from resolution to print speed.

---

## What Is an Objective (And Why Should I Care)?

In the GT2, the **objective lens** is the heart of the entire printing process. It is a precision microscope lens that focuses the laser to a tiny point inside the photoresist. Everything about your print — resolution, speed, voxel size, compatible materials, and achievable structure size — is determined by which objective you choose.

Think of it like choosing a brush for painting: a fine brush gives you detail but takes longer; a wide brush is fast but rough.

---

## The 4 Objectives Available

The Photonic Professional GT2 comes with **4 interchangeable objectives**:

| Objective | Magnification | Type | NA | Working Distance | Mode | Primary Use |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **25× DiLL** | 25× | Immersion | 0.8 | 380 µm | DiLL | Mesoscale balanced printing |
| **63× DiLL** | 63× | Oil Immersion | 1.4 | 360 µm | DiLL / Oil | Highest resolution nanostructures |
| **10× DiLL** | 10× | Immersion | 0.3 | 700 µm | DiLL | Large mm-scale fast prints |
| **20× Air** | 20× | Air | — | — | Air | 2D / pseudo-3D on spin-coated resists |

> ⚠️ **Critical:** You must physically swap objectives when changing between modes. The wrong objective with the wrong resist can damage the lens or your sample.

